      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the pedicle screw and vertebral body surrogate assembly. QoI values (stiffness, yield force) changed by less than 1.5% between medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation confirmed discretization error contribution below 2%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals converge to below 1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance checked at each increment.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analyses used Newton-Raphson iteration with force and displacement convergence criteria of 1e-6. Energy balance was verified at each load increment. No spurious oscillations or divergence events were observed across the load range."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent analyst review of model setup, boundary conditions, and load application; checklist-based verification against ASTM F1717 fixture geometry.",
      "rationale": "An independent analyst reviewed all model setup files, boundary condition definitions, and load application scripts against the ASTM F1717 test fixture specification. No use errors were identified. Checklist documented and archived."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum solid mechanics with nonlinear material and contact formulations selected; justification documented against known failure modes (plastic hinge at screw-rod interface).",
      "rationale": "The FEA employs continuum solid elements with bilinear isotropic hardening for the titanium alloy components and frictional contact at screw-rod and screw-vertebra interfaces. This model form is well-established for metallic implant compression-bending simulation and captures the dominant failure mode (plastic hinge formation) observed experimentally."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (E, yield stress, tangent modulus) sourced from coupon tests of same lot material; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of tested constructs.",
      "rationale": "Titanium alloy material properties were characterized from dogbone coupon specimens cut from the same material lot as the tested pedicle screws. Construct geometry was measured using coordinate measuring machine (CMM) on three representative specimens. Input uncertainty was propagated using a Monte Carlo approach (n=1000 samples)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs tested; samples are production-representative parts from same manufacturing lot; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to drawing.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All samples were production-representative parts from the same manufacturing lot. Dimensional inspection confirmed conformance to engineering drawings within specified tolerances."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least two distinct load configurations or fixture offsets tested to characterize condition sensitivity; environmental conditions (temperature, humidity) monitored and reported.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 load configuration (44 mm offset). No alternative fixture offsets or load angles were evaluated. This limits the ability to assess model sensitivity to test condition variation. Achieved level (1) is below required level (2); this gap is acknowledged and accepted given the standardized nature of the F1717 protocol and the corroborating multi-lab data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to as-tested conditions; traceability matrix linking model parameters to measured specimen properties.",
      "rationale": "A traceability matrix was constructed linking each FEA input parameter to the corresponding measured or specified value from the physical test specimens. Geometry was taken from CMM measurements; material properties from coupon tests on same-lot material; boundary conditions replicated the ASTM F1717 fixture constraints. Equivalency confirmed for all primary inputs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric; E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm); percent difference < 10% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "The validation metric E/uval (ratio of model error to combined validation uncertainty) was computed for all three QoIs. Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.84 (6.2% diff), yield force E/uval = 1.21 (7.8% diff), force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.03 (5.1% diff). All values are below the acceptance threshold of 1.96 and percent differences are below 10%. Validation is considered successful."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements; linkage documented.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are those specified in ASTM F1717 and directly correspond to the mechanical performance attributes reviewed in FDA 510(k) submissions for pedicle screw systems. Stiffness characterizes construct rigidity; yield force identifies onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm represents post-yield load-carrying capacity. All three are clinically and regulatorily relevant."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (ASTM F1717 bench test) is directly representative of the COU (regulatory submission supporting non-cannulated pedicle screw design); same device, same test standard, same QoIs.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is a direct replication of the regulatory test scenario: same device design, same test standard (ASTM F1717), same QoIs, and same acceptance criteria as would be applied in a 510(k) submission. The validation scenario is therefore maximally relevant to the COU, supporting a high relevance gradation."
